The 9.3x74mmR is of a rimmed, bottleneck design and uses a .366-inch (9.3 mm) diameter bullet, usually weighing 286-grain (18.5 g). According to Hornady, at this weight the velocity is 2,360 ft/s (720 m/s) and energy is 3,536 ft·lbf (4,794 J). This cartridge is used for CXP2 and CXP3 types of game (medium and heavy animals) and is very popular in Europe for wild boar. Initially designed for large European game like moose, brown bear, and polar bear, it started following hunters on safaris. It remains a popular cartridge in African hunting in countries with more German influence like Namibia, favored as a continental alternative to the more popular .375 H&H Magnum.

title: For Sale:  RJ II
postcontent:
The smaller brother of the tactical RJ I $32.33

RJ Martin’s blade design and grind gives you the piercing power of a tanto with just enough curve to the belly for slicing aptitude as well. The tanto point is even stronger than comparable tantos because Kershaw makes the tip thicker and gives it a tough flat grind. The result is an über-strong tip that takes on the toughest piercing tasks with no fear. But the RJ II isn’t done yet.

This knife offers a full range of cutting edges. The plain edge is ever so slightly curved, giving the RJ II slicing capability—something not all tanto blades offer. In addition, the blade is partially serrated to make cutting through tough or fibrous materials a breeze. The blade is made of 8Cr13MoV stainless steel that’s tough, wear resistant, and takes a keen edge. For a distinctive look and enhanced performance, the blade is coated with titanium carbo-nitride.

The RJ II also features 3-D machined G-10 handle scales and a secure stainless-steel locking liner. It opens with one-handed ease thanks to the SpeedSafe assisted opening system. Access it with the built-in flipper or thumbstud. The pocketclip is reversible for tip-up or tip-down carry. Tactical looks and a multifunctional blade combine in the RJ II—also available in a larger size as the RJ I.

 Technical Specifications
•2-Step Serration
Serrations assist in cutting through particularly tough or fibrous material, such as rope or cord. The Kershaw 2-step serration is a more aggressive style of serration.

•Flipper
May be used on either manual or assisted opening knives. The “flipper” is a protrusion on the back of the blade that the user can pull back on, or flip, in order to move the blade easily out of the handle.

•SpeedSafe®
Assists you to open any SpeedSafe® knife quickly and easily with a manual push on the thumbstud or pull back on the flipper; built into many Kershaw best sellers.

•Liner Lock
Locks the blade open during use; one side of the knife’s steel “liner,” the steel plate to which the handle scales are attached, moves into position behind the blade to securely lock it open.

•Reversible
Pre-drilled holes in the handle enable the user to change either the tip position or the side on which the knife carries.

title: For Sale:  SKS your way
postcontent:
I had an SKS that I modified and ended up trading it to a friend for some cash and his Norinco SKS.  I started working on it but the opportunity came up for me to purchase another rifle that I'd like to have.  I decided to sell this SKS once I complete the project.

So... that got me thinking, instead of just making it how I like it, maybe I'd post it for sale now and give the purchaser options so it could be finished according to their preferences.

So far it's been shortened to 16.5" with the barrel crowned to 11 degrees.  Debating on putting a muzzle break or flash hider on it (or leaving it with the target crown), I'll leave this up to you.  It's currently in the raw (bare steel); I was going to Parkerize it, but figured the purchaser may want it blued, so I'll leave that option up to you.  I should note, when I say blued, I don't mean that "cold blue" rub on chemicals, I mean hot blueing (blueing salts at 290 degrees type).  

I was in the middle of a trigger job, but the pins on the trigger are kind of a bear, couldn't get them punched out for the life of me.  Drilling them out would probably alter the tolerances of the holes, so I plan on just getting a replacement trigger group.  I may or may not do a trigger job on it, depending on the purchaser.

I have a wood stock, was looking at the Tapco stocks, but figured someone may want a side-folder or the strikeforce.  

For optics, I can get the rail cover picitanny rail pretty cheap but don't believe those hold zero as well.  I'll most likely be getting the mount that replaces the rear site.  Again, this is up to you.

If there's any interest, let me know.  I'm sure we can negotiate a price.  I can either do the work and hand it over, or if someone is interested in taking part, we can do it together.  This will be a really nice rifle.

I'm not a bubba (I do pretty good work if I do say so myself... my friend who wanted my other SKS would probably agree).  If you have any questions regarding any of the modifications, feel free to ask.  even if you're not interested in the rifle, I don't mind answering questions or giving you tips so you can do work on your own guns.

Lastly, if there are any other mods you may want that I didn't mention, we can talk about them (i.e. bolt closed magazine insertion).  Hope to hear from someone who will appreciate a nice rifle and the blood, sweat, and tears that goes into a quality custom job.

title: For Sale:  AZ/FL Concealed Carry / NRA Basic Pistol Sun July 14 - $125

postcontent:
NRA Basic Pistol by Allguntraining.com
Qualifies for Arizona and Florida Concealed Carry Permit.
Should meet the first 8 hours of training required for IL.*
Taking our class now will automatically put you on the waiting list for our IL specific class (second 8 hours) when we become IL certified.
IL residents will need other state permits like AZ or FL to carry outside of IL since IL won't have reciprocity agreements.*
It is a good idea to have more then one CCW permit due to changes in reciprocity.
Reciprocity is when one state agrees to honor another states permit, meaning you can then carry in another state.
   *HB0183/SB2193  not signed into law yet.  
CCW applications will be available at class

To register for class visit-
Sunday June 30
   http://allguntraining.com/class_schedule/

About the class-
Classroom and Range are at the same location.
Peotone IL about 45 miles south of Chicago
Class is 8+ hours long.
You can bring your own firearms and ammo or use our guns and buy or ammo.
We have guns in 22, 9mm, 38 special and 45 acp.
Try out some different calibers/guns before you buy one.

FOID not needed to take the class as long as you are not a prohibited person, if you could legally own a gun but are waiting for your FOID card then you can take the class.
You do need a FOID if you transport your own guns/ammo to class.

A minimum of 50 rounds is required, please bring more, we try to shoot 75-100 rounds or more if possible.
We like to shoot.

What the Class covers-
Firearm Safety, this is first and foremost a firearm safety class, the only way to fail is to be dangerous on the range/classroom.
Types of handguns- Revolvers / Semiautomatics
Actions-  Single Action only / Double Action-Single Action / Double Action Only / Striker Fired
Major parts of a Revolver, Frame, Barrel, Cylinder, trigger, trigger guard, handgrips, etc.
Major parts of a Semi Automatic- Frame, Barrel, magazine, trigger guard, handgrips, etc.
Ammunition- Centerfire / Rimfire, Full Jacketed / Lead,  Hollow Point / Wadcutter / Round nose
How to pick the right ammo for your gun-  Caliber, Standard pressure / +P pressure ,
  Ex.  Learn the difference between different 9mm rounds
   9mm Luger, 9mm Parabellum, 9mm NATO, 9mmx19mm (all the same round, just different names.
   9x18 or 9mm Makerov different ammo and I've seen people buy it for their 9mm Parabellum guns and it wouldn't work.
   There are many more ammunition differences to watch out for, like 45 ACP vs 45 GAP vs 45 Colt.

Shooting stances-  Isosceles, Weaver, Single handed and proper grip.
Fundamentals of shooting- Breath control, sight alignment, trigger control, follow through.

Cover laws on firearm purchasing and transport.
Learn about other shooting opportunities.

And much more.

Private classes, ladies only, weekday and weeknight classes available.
Please contact with your availability, we are trying to schedule more classes to meet students needs.

Contact us for more info or to inquire about additional class availability.
